{"questionId":"27704","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A particle moves in a straight line. Its displacement, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>s</mi></math> metres, from a fixed point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>P</mtext></math> at&nbsp;time <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> seconds is given by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>s</mi><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>cos</mi><mo> </mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup></math>, for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>≤</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>≤</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn></math>, as shown in the following graph.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/0f93d8dfeb35b4287bd371d2a42be592699f154c.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The acceleration of the particle is zero when <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>b</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>c</mi></math>, where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>c</mi></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the total distance travelled by the particle for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>b</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>c</mi></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><strong>METHOD 1</strong> (using integral of velocity)</p>\n<p>correct integral (accept absence of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></math>)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mo>∫</mo><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>23140</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>68959</mn><mo>…</mo></mrow></msubsup><mfen